storians but also politicians, ecclesiastics, journalists and campaigners argued about interpretations of the Reformation and the motivations of its principal agents. The author also shows how, in the twentieth century, the debate was influenced by the development of history as a subject and, in the twenty-first century, by state control of the academy. Undergraduates, researchers and lecturers alike will find this an invaluable and essential companion to their studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReformationzEnglandxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aChurch of England.  aEnglish Reformation.  aEnglish people.  aHenry VIII.  aJohn Strype.  aProtestantism.  aReformation historiography.  aThomas Fuller.  aTudor revolution.  acontemporary politics.  amodern debate.  apeer review.  apostmodernist theory.  areligious identities.1 aO’Day, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610166240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101662/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles